    <item>
      <title>Non-oriented Lookat</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/shorts/fast-lookat/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 07 May 2025 16:44:00 +0200</pubDate><author>carve.chris@gmail.com (Chris Carvelli)</author>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/shorts/fast-lookat/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Useful when we want to have an object pointing in the direction of a vector, but we don&amp;rsquo;t care about orientation.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s important to note that this is not just a potential optimization. Not having an &lt;code&gt;up&lt;/code&gt; vector means that we don&amp;rsquo;t have to worry about degenerate cases where &lt;code&gt;up&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;dir&lt;/code&gt; are aligned.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The classic use case (and the reason I put this together) is to compute the world matrix of debug rays and gizmo arms. Using &lt;code&gt;lookAt&lt;/code&gt; to draw force applications and basis vectors is annoying and error-prone, all to draw entities that don&amp;rsquo;t have an orientation anyway.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
